Directly read from warpdotdev/warp AGPL source at commit a44b703. The evidence is multi-layered and specific:

---

## 1. How Warp's Input Editor / Block Model Works (Architecture)

Warp intercepted the classic shell-readline loop and moved the entire command editor into the terminal process itself. The PTY is set to raw mode but the user's characters are captured by Warp's editor; the composed command is written to the PTY only on Enter. Source: [Warp blog on terminal input architecture](https://www.warp.dev/blog/why-is-the-terminal-input-so-weird).

The input editor is **pinned to the bottom** of the pane (by default). As commands execute, "blocks" — grouped command + output units — grow upward from the input. This gives Warp's distinctive layout: scrollback of blocks above, static input box below.

**Key distinction from a dumb terminal**: Warp holds the editor state locally. It only forwards characters to the PTY at submission. This is why completions, syntax highlighting, multi-line editing, and the Ctrl-G rich editor can all exist at the terminal layer without cooperation from the shell.

---

## 2. Alt-Screen Detection and Chrome Suppression — Confirmed from Source

From `app/src/terminal/model/terminal_model.rs` ([Sourcegraph](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/warpdotdev/Warp@a44b703060673b85d2641c051c53e4b6b1b00cc4/-/blob/app/src/terminal/model/terminal_model.rs%3FL1008-1025)):

```rust
pub enum TerminalInputState {
    /// Alt-screen on which programs like vim run is visible.
    AltScreen,
    /// Warp Input View is visible.
    InputEditor,
    /// Block-list is visible but input will go to the running command.
    LongRunningCommand,
    /// Terminal hasn't finished bootstrapping and can't receive any input.
    NotBootstrapped,
}

pub fn terminal_input_state(&self) -> TerminalInputState {
    if !self.block_list().is_bootstrapped() {
        TerminalInputState::NotBootstrapped
    } else if self.is_alt_screen_active() {
        TerminalInputState::AltScreen        // ← vim, htop, btop, Claude Code fullscreen
    } else if self.block_list().active_block().is_active_and_long_running() {
        TerminalInputState::LongRunningCommand  // ← e.g. Claude Code default TUI
    } else {
        TerminalInputState::InputEditor      // ← normal shell prompt
    }
}
```

And from `app/src/terminal/event.rs` ([Sourcegraph](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/warpdotdev/Warp@a44b703060673b85d2641c051c53e4b6b1b00cc4/-/blob/app/src/terminal/event.rs%3FL177-181)):

```rust
pub enum TerminalMode {
    AltScreen,
    BlockList,
}
```

**How AltScreen suppresses the input editor and block chrome:**

From `app/src/terminal/view/init.rs` ([Sourcegraph](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/warpdotdev/Warp@a44b703060673b85d2641c051c53e4b6b1b00cc4/-/blob/app/src/terminal/view/init.rs%3FL120-350)):

Key bindings for block selection (expand_block_selection_above/below) use the context predicate `& !id!("AltScreen")` — they are disabled when alt-screen is active.

The Ctrl-G CLI agent rich input binding fires on `(id!("LongRunningCommand") | id!("AltScreen"))`, confirming **both** states keep the CLI agent footer/toolbelt alive.

From the cloud-mode-input-v2 spec (`specs/cloud-mode-input-v2/TECH.md` line 166):

```rust
// In the main pane render:
column.add_child(Shrinkable::new(1., output_area).finish());
if model.is_alt_screen_active() && self.should_render_use_agent_footer(&model, app) {
    column.add_child(ChildView::new(&self.use_agent_footer).finish());
}
if self.is_input_box_visible(&model, app) {
    column.add_child(self.render_input());
}
```

This shows: when alt-screen is active, `output_area` renders the `AltScreenElement` (not the block list). The `is_input_box_visible` check gates whether the Warp input editor appears at all. The agent footer (toolbelt) is conditionally shown even during AltScreen if a CLI agent session is active.

**The suppression mechanism is**: `TerminalInputState::AltScreen` causes `is_input_box_visible` to return false, so the Warp input editor is not rendered. The `AltScreenElement` occupies the full pane content area. The block list is not rendered (it's the alternate path). The pane layout switches from [blocks + input editor] to [AltScreen + optional CLI agent footer].

**Precise claim from the claim-to-verify**: "Mode::AltScreen detection suppresses overlay chrome" — **confirmed**, with the mechanism being: `is_alt_screen_active()` → `TerminalInputState::AltScreen` → `is_input_box_visible()` returns false → input editor not rendered; AltScreenElement rendered instead. The `id!("AltScreen")` context key is set on the terminal view, disabling block-selection bindings and enabling alt-screen-specific ones. This is directly in the AGPL source, not a DeepWiki synthesis.

---

## 3. What Warp's CLI Agent Footer Does During AltScreen (Critical for the User's Context)

From `app/src/terminal/input/cli_agent.rs` ([Sourcegraph](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/warpdotdev/Warp@a44b703060673b85d2641c051c53e4b6b1b00cc4/-/blob/app/src/terminal/input/cli_agent.rs%3FL95-175)):

```rust
// When an alt screen CLI agent (e.g. OpenCode) is running, match
// the rich input background to the alt screen so it blends in.
{
    let terminal_model = self.model.lock();
    if terminal_model.is_alt_screen_active() {
        if let Some(bg_color) = terminal_model.alt_screen().inferred_bg_color() {
            input_container = input_container.with_background(bg_color);
        }
    }
}
```

This explicitly documents that **OpenCode** (an alt-screen TUI agent) is a known case. Warp detects it's running on top of an alt-screen CLI agent and color-matches the rich input background to the agent's background so it visually "blends in." The Ctrl-G rich input editor is **drawn on top of** the alt-screen content at the bottom of the pane.

So the layout during Claude Code (default TUI = `LongRunningCommand`) or OpenCode (alt-screen TUI = `AltScreen`) is:
- Full pane: the CLI agent's TUI output (block list or alt-screen)
- Bottom overlay: the Warp CLI agent footer / toolbelt (notifications, rich input toggle)
- On Ctrl-G: the rich input editor slides up as a panel above the toolbelt, cursor is hidden inside the CLI agent

---

## 4. Claude Code in Warp Specifically

**Claude Code default mode (non-fullscreen)**: Claude Code renders via its line-by-line TUI approach. From Warp's perspective, this is `TerminalInputState::LongRunningCommand` — the block-list is still visible but the running command's output streams in. Warp's input editor is hidden. The CLI agent toolbelt appears at the bottom. Ctrl-G opens the Warp rich input editor as an overlay panel. From [Warp docs](https://docs.warp.dev/agent-platform/cli-agents/claude-code/): "Warp auto-detects Claude Code when you run it, giving you access to rich input controls, code review, agent notifications."

**Claude Code fullscreen mode (`/tui fullscreen` or `CLAUDE_CODE_NO_FLICKER=1`)**: Claude Code uses the terminal's alternate screen buffer, like vim. From Warp's perspective, this is `TerminalInputState::AltScreen`. The AltScreenElement renders the full pane. The Warp CLI agent footer can still appear (conditioned on `should_render_use_agent_footer`). Ctrl-G still works (context predicate includes AltScreen). From [Claude Code fullscreen docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/fullscreen): "It draws the interface on the terminal's alternate screen buffer, like vim or htop... The input box stays fixed at the bottom of the screen."

**Warp Native Agent Mode vs Claude Code CLI**: These are distinct. Warp's native Oz agent is built into Warp and does not run a CLI TUI at all. Running Claude Code gives you the Claude Code TUI (Warp is a host). Warp adds the toolbelt and rich input around it but does NOT replace Claude Code's UI. The warpdotdev/claude-code-warp plugin communicates via OSC 777 escape sequences to Warp's notification center. From [DeepWiki](https://deepwiki.com/warpdotdev/claude-code-warp/3-how-it-works): `\033]777;notify;<title>;<body>\007` written to /dev/tty.

---

## 5. Feasibility of Warp-Style Separate Input Box on Your libghostty Stack

**Shell command (line-based, no TUI running)**: Fully feasible. This is exactly what Warp does. You capture the PTY before the shell gets it, run a native editor in a pinned native pane, submit the composed command to the PTY on Enter. Your constraints: libghostty surface API is opaque (VT stream passthrough, no parsed grid). You would need to intercept bytes between host PTY and libghostty rendering surface, or run a parallel PTY that your native editor writes to. This is architecturally the same as what Warp built from scratch in Rust.

**Long-running TUI programs (Claude Code default, vim, htop)**: The input box must be hidden or switched to raw passthrough. Warp's `TerminalInputState::LongRunningCommand` hides the input editor and just lets the PTY stream render. For Claude Code specifically: Claude Code default mode is a TUI — it owns the input. You cannot show a separate native input box for Claude Code's prompt without bypassing Claude Code's TUI entirely.

**Claude Code via Agent SDK**: If you drive Claude Code through `claude --output-format stream-json` (non-interactive mode), Claude Code never shows its TUI. You send prompts programmatically, receive structured JSON events, and can render the conversation in a fully native pane with your own input box. This is the architecture needed for a "Warp-style box outside Claude Code." The tradeoff is losing Claude Code's interactive TUI features (slash commands UI, tool approval dialogs, etc.) — you'd need to implement those natively or via the SDK's tool-call approval flow.

**The key tension confirmed**: A Warp-style separate input box and a full-screen TUI are mutually exclusive in the same pane. Warp resolves this by hiding the input editor during AltScreen/LongRunningCommand and only showing the CLI agent footer (a minimal chrome element). For a truly native input box experience with Claude Code, the user's only architecturally clean path is Agent SDK driving, not Claude Code TUI passthrough.
